# Git Commit & Push After Every Code Change

After completing ANY code modification (adding features, fixing bugs, refactoring, config changes), you MUST:

## 1. Stage and Commit

```bash
git add -A
git commit -m "$(cat <<'EOF'
<type>(<scope>): <short summary>

<optional body: what changed and why>
EOF
)"
```

**Commit message types:** `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `docs`, `chore`, `perf`, `test`

## 2. Create a Version Tag

Use semantic versioning: `v<MAJOR>.<MINOR>.<PATCH>`

- **PATCH** (+0.0.1): bug fix, small tweak
- **MINOR** (+0.1.0): new feature, new module
- **MAJOR** (+1.0.0): breaking change, major restructure

```bash
# Get the last tag to decide the next version
git tag --sort=-v:refname | head -5

# Create annotated tag
git tag -a v0.X.Y -m "v0.X.Y: <one-line description of this version>"
```

## 3. Push Branch + Tag

```bash
git push origin master && git push origin v0.X.Y
```

## 4. Report to User

After pushing, report:
- Commit hash (short)
- Tag created (e.g. `v0.2.1`)
- A one-line summary of what changed
- How to roll back: `git checkout v0.X.Y` or `git revert <hash>`

## Rollback Reference

Tell user they can revert with:
```bash
# Roll back to a specific version (non-destructive)
git revert <commit-hash>

# Or restore to a tagged version (creates new branch from tag)
git checkout -b rollback-v0.X.Y v0.X.Y
```
